column12: Aluminum dust collection and compacting apparatus
column13: An apparatus for collecting dust from a cutting unit is provided. The apparatus includes a rotary valve operatively connected to the cutting unit, a conduit in fluid communication with the rotary valve, and a compacting machine disposed downstream from the conduit and configured to receive dust from the conduit. A blower is configured to pull air downstream to carry the dust into the compacting machine. The compacting machine produces a compact from the dust.

column12: Air transportable container adjunct
column13: The skid device of the present invention includes two skid plates having a rectangular configuration. Each of the skid plates are mounted underneath a flatrack container along an underside longitudinal edge portion of the flatrack. The mounting to the underside is through a plurality of linkages having one end secured to the top of each of the skid and the second end secured to the underside of the flatracker container. The linkages are dimensioned and provided with a drive for progressively lowering the skid whereby the flatrack container rests on the skids when so desired. Locks are provided whereby the linkages may be locked at one of several altitudes. The drive also returns the skid to its folded position in confronting relationship with the underside of the flatrack container and the latter rests on two beams spaced from a longitudinal centerline of the flatrack container. The drive is generally disposed to drive the respective linkages of both skids simultaneously.

column12: Improvements in pressure vessels
column13: 806,616. Doors for resisting fluid pressure. WHESSOE Ltd. July 30, 1957 [April 30, 1956], No. 13170/56. Class 123(1) A large rectangular opening in the curved wall of a cylindrical pressure vessel formed of steel plates 5 stiffened by external annular girders 6, 7 is covered by a removable door formed of curved plates 10 stiffened by girders 11, 13. Along the longitudinal edges of the opening are welded reinforcing bars 8 each having a tapered groove in which engages a key projection 16 formed integrally upon the inner surface of each of two reinforcing bars 14 which are welded along the longitudinal edges of the door. The ends of the bars 8 are connected by curved bars 9 to complete the frame surrounding the opening, the bars 19 being formed without the tapered groove. Curved bars 15 formed without a projecting key connect the ends of the bars 14 on the door. The door is secured by a double row of studs 17 along the longitudinal edges and a single row of studs passing through bushes 20 at the ends. Hoop stresses are transmitted to and through the door by the keys 16 but longitudinal stresses are transmitted by the shell wall and its reinforcing bars 8 and not through the door. A gas seal extends completely around the opening, the seal being formed by an inflatable rubber ring which is accommodated in a groove 21 in the bars 8, 9.

column12: Freight containers lifting means
column13: A hook-lift vehicle provided with a hydraulically-operated lifting mechanism on its chassis is adapted to handle freight containers having conventional corner fittings, by an adaptor frame (2) for attachment to the lifting mechanisms and including twistlocks for securing with the end corner fittings of a container. The twistlocks are secured to a rigid part (4) of the frame, provided with a hook lift bar (6), and to a pair of telescopic arms (12) pivoted to the rigid part. A pair of spaced support surfaces (18) are located on an outrigger (16) and pivotal about an axis transverse of the chassis at the rear end thereof whereby, subsequent to securing the adaptor frame (2) to the front of a container on the ground and an actuating the lifting mechanism, the front of the container is drawn upwardly onto the chassis until the outer lower side regions of the container engage the support surfaces (18), continued actuation of the lifting mechanism drawing the container over the pivoting surfaces (18) and onto the chassis. The surface may be low friction blocks or a high friction continuous belt. <IMAGE>
column15: BISHOP FRANK WALTER

column13: The lifting device has a hydraulically-operated lifting mechanism (46) on the chassis, and an adaptor frame (2) for attachment to mechanism and container. The adaptor frame includes securing members (12, 22) co-operating with corner fittings (52, 54) of the container. A pair of laterally-spaced support surfaces (34) provide means of locating the device to chassis of the vehicle. The surfaces are pivotal and extend transversely along the chassis, spaced apart by distance equal to the width of the container. column12: Linear motion cable drive - has drive cable wrapped helically on driven cable and rotated to cancel effects of helical wrapping
column13: The linear cable drive comprises a series of drive assemblies cooperating to drive a cable. Each assembly includes a drive cable helically engaged around the periphery of the driven cable. The cable is driven in the helical path and also rotated with its drive, about the axis of the driven cable at such a rate and in a direction so as to unwrap the forward end of the drive cable. This negates any rotational forces imparted to the driven cable by the helical path. A length of driven cable is allowed to pass which has a peripheral dimension that varies from the base peripheral dimension without imparting rotational forces to it.

column12: Shaft coupler
column13: The present invention relates generally to improvements in shaft coupler devices and more particularly to improved coupler devices in the nature of torque limiting clutch mechanisms. An embodiment of the present invention disclosed herein includes a plurality of yieldable beam members adapted to be supported by and to rotate with a driven shaft, the inner surfaces of said yieldable beam members being uniformally oriented circumferentially about and spaced from the axis of an associated supporting shaft so as to define a non-circular opening for accommodating a plurality of rotary coupling members as for example a plurality of rollers. These rollers revolve as a unit with and about the axis of a driving shaft and are maintained in engagement with the inner surface area of the yieldable beam members.

column12: Load carrying platforms
column13: There is disclosed a cargo holder having a planar bottom of a rectangularly shaped configuration. The bottom has two depending girders along its longest dimension. They are each spaced from a center imaginary line. The shortest ends of the bottom has a depending wall with an opening between the said girders. The bottom corners of the depending wall has a corner fact. The same shortest ends of the bottom also has foldable upstanding end walls which terminate at each of the corners at the top with corner fitments. The end walls are designed to fold inwardly downwardly in confrontation with the bottom of the cargo holder so that the cargo holder, when empty and the end walls folded, may be easily stacked to thereby conserve space. The end walls are horizontally hinged at proximate the bottom. The hinge however is essentially by-passed for any weight distribution that may be imposed on the top of the end wall when any loaded cargo holders are stacked thereon top as the end walls rest directly on an unique surface provided along the side ends of the upwardly facing portion of the depending wall. The end walls are also provided with a biasing structure to bias the end wall upwardly while at the same time to supply no bias when the end walls are folded downwardly.
column15: BISHOP FRANK W

column12: Improvements in load supporting means
column13: 813,623. Tanks. WHESSOE Ltd. April 11, 1957 [Jan. 11, 1956],No. 971/56. Class 69 (1). In a vessel having an internal structure in the form of a substantially circular and horizontal load supporting platform 8 disposed within and spaced from the shell 1 of the vessel, the platform is supported from the lower part of the shell by a plurality of vertical columns 9 distributed around the periphery of the platform, each column having a cross-section whose radial dimension is small compared with its tangential dimension, so that horizontal expansion and contraction of the platform relative to the shell 1 of the vessel is permitted by simultaneous outward or inward bending of all the columns, whilst the platform is held against horizontal movement as a whole by the high resistance of each column to bending in a tangential direction. The vessel is supported on brackets 5 secured to the shell of the vessel and bearing on the upper ends of rocking columns 6. Internal brackets 7 are provided above the brackets 5 and serve to support the internal structure. Each of the columns 9 is supported on one of the brackets 7. As shown in Fig. 1, the platform 8 is rigidly supported on the column 9. In a modification shown in Fig. 3 the column 9 is provided with a cap plate 11a having a cylindrically curved surface. The platform 8 is provided with a recessed bearing plate 13 which rests on the cap plate 11a and makes a rolling contact therewith along a line directed tangentially of the vessel. Specifications 813,621, 813,622 and 813,624 are referred to.

column13: En la presente se describen compuestos, composiciones y métodos para modular el corte y empalme de ARNm SMN2 en un sujeto. También se proporcionan usos de las composiciones y compuestos descritos en la elaboración de un medicamento para el tratamiento de enfermedades y trastornos, que incluyen atrofia muscular espinal. También se proporcionan kits para detectar la cantidad de proteína SMN en una muestra de líquido cefalorraquídeo.

column12: Improvements in load supporting means
column13: 813,624. Tanks. WHESSOE Ltd. April 11, 1957 [Jan. 11, 1956], No. 972/56. Class 69 (1). In a vessel having an internal structure in the form of a circular and horizontal load carrying platform disposed within and spaced from the shell 1 of the vessel, the perimeter girder 2 of the platform rests on the upper ends of roller support members 9 which rest at their lower ends upon brackets 3 fast with the shell, the support members being distributed around the centre of the platform and each having its upper and lower end surfaces shaped as parts of a cylinder whose axis is disposed horizontally and perpendicular to the radius of the platform which passes through that support member. The roller support members 9 are arranged in two groups of three in a pair of radial grooves 8 formed in bearing plates 4, 5. The three rollers of each group are held spaced apart by a pair of end plates 10 secured to the rollers by bolts 11 which allow the rollers to rack relative to the end plates. Specifications 813,621 and 813,622 are referred to.

column12: New or improved method for marking out work
column13: 834,697. Marking-out work. WHESSOE Ltd. July 4, 1958 [July 17, 1957], No. 22636/57. Addition to 806,347. Class 61. An improvement in or modification of the method of marking out a workpiece, of the parent Specification, consists in interposing one or more reflecting surfaces in the path of light from the source to the workpiece. In one arrangement a downwardly facing, horizontally disposed mirror 31 is supported at a distance a above the template 16 and a light source 10 is disposed beneath the mirror at a distance b from it such that a + b = d where d is the distance above the template 16 of the centre of curvature 0 of the plate 24 to be marked. In a modification a second horizontal plane mirror is used. In another modification a curved mirror is arranged so that a virtual image of the source 10 is produced at the centre of curvature of the plate. In other modifications the light source is off-set from the vertical axis of the apparatus.
column15: BISHOP RONALD FRANK;;WILLIAMS HARRY

column12: Improvements relating to the testing of vessels for ability to withstand internal pressure
column13: 837,951. Testing strength of hollow bodies. WHESSOE Ltd. July 17, 1958 [July 31, 1957], No. 24271/57. Class 106 (2). A body to be tested, e.g. the pressure vessel of a nuclear reactor, is filled with liquid under pressure and at the same time is immersed partly or completely in liquid. A preliminary test of the vessel is made with air supplied by a compressor 6. The vessel is then filled with water through a pipe 10, stand-pipes 24, 25 being closed after the water has overflowed from them, and a vent 26 being used to remove air from the very top of the vessel. At the same time the space between the biological shield 4 and the vessel is also filled with water through a pipe 11. By this means, the additional thrust on the supports 3 is relatively low. After being filled, pressurized water is supplied through a pipe 18, careful observation being kept on a pressure-gauge 20, on which leakage is indicated by a sudden fall in pressure. In modifications, Figs. 2 and 3 (not shown), the water in which the vessel 1 is immersed is contained in a steel tank erected within the biological shield 4.

column12: Improvements relating to heat insulation
column13: 851,458. Nuclear reactors. WHESSOE Ltd. March 31, 1959 [Dec. 31, 1957], No. 40448/57. Class 39(4). The interior surface of a nuclear reactor pressure vessel is protected by a heat insulating covering formed of sheets of stainless steel, corrugated to contain pockets of gas. The covering is secured by bolts welded to the shell inner surface. As shown, the inner surface of the pressure vessel 10 is covered by the metal sheets 11, 12 which are spaced by the corrugations in 11. The cover plates are urged against 11, 12 by the nut 16 on stud 15 welded to 10. The bolt and nut assembly is covered by the dome 19, which supports the insulating sheets 17, 18 and is welded to 13. To limit the compression of the insulation by plate 13 the ferrule 20 is threaded over bolt 15. In other embodiments, not shown, ferrule may be replaced by a shoulder on the bolt and the nut thermally insulated from the plate 13 by a disc of ceramic material. Pipes or ducts which project into the vessel are protected by similar covering.

In a nuclear fuel element comprising a fuel member 42 in a protective sheath 43 provided with end-locating members 46, 47, a non-fissile member is arranged to provide a void space adjacent an end of the fuel member to accommodate local end growth of the fuel, said non-fissile member being of material having a neutron absorption cross-section greater than that of the fuel. Overheating at the end of the fuel element is thus avoided. As shown, boron steel caps 78, 79 are screwed on to reduced end portions of the fuel member leaving voids 82, 83 with vent holes 80, 81. Other features are heat insulating alumina discs 62, 63, circumferential grooves 48 into which the sheath is indented, and thin uranium rings 74, 75 to assist detection of leakage. The Provisional Specification also describes an element in which boron steel dowel members are provided in sockets in the end locating members; this Specification also states that if the caps 78, 79 are made of cobalt steel, they may be removed after a period of irradiation and used for medical purposes. Specification 939,183 is referred to.

column12: Improvements in Steam Boiler Furnaces.
column13: 11,136. Bishop, G. M., and Hughes, F. J. June 19. Fireboxes; stays; tubes, water.-Relates mainly to means for supplying air to steam-generator fireboxes. Fig. 1 is a vertical section of a locomotive firebox, showing one method of carrying the invention into effect. Air is supplied through perforated firebars, and through the tubular stays 11, the openings through which are larger towards the bottom of the firebox, where the air supply is required to be greatest. Fig. 2 shows a modified form of firebox, in which the sides are vertical and the stays solid. At one or each side of the firebox is placed a zig-zagged tube 21, arranged so that the spaces between its horizontal portions are larger towards the bottom to allow a larger passage for the air there. These tubes are connected to the water space, and improve the circulation.

column13: Die vorliegende Offenbarung stellt ein System und Verfahren zum radialen Ausrichten einer stranggepressten Rohrleitung für eine Fahrzeugkarosseriekomponente bereit. Es ist ein Verfahren zum Ausrichten einer Schweißnaht in einem Aluminiumrohr einer Fahrzeugkarosserie bereitgestellt. Das Verfahren kann das Messen eines Umfangs eines ersten Endes des Rohrs zum Ermitteln einer Position einer Zacke, die an einer Wand des ersten Endes des Rohrs angeordnet ist, und das Drehen des Rohrs, sodass die Schweißnaht in einer vorbestimmten Lage, die zum Formen des Rohrs geeignet ist, positioniert wird, beinhalten.

column12: Delivery of low pressure dopant gas to a high voltage ion source
column13: A system for delivery of low-pressure dopant gas to a high-voltage ion source in the doping of semiconductor substrates, in which undesired ionization of the gas is suppressed prior to entry into the high-voltage ion source, by modulating electron energy upstream of the high-voltage ion source so that electron acceleration effects are reduced to below a level supporting an electronic ionization cascade. The gas delivery system in a specific application includes a gas flow passage, a voltage generator electrically coupled with at least a portion of the gas flow passage to impose an electric field thereon, and an obstructive structure that is deployed to modulate acceleration length of electrons of the low-pressure gas in relation to ionization potential of the gas, to suppress ionization in the gas flow passage.

column12: Magnesium ion based synaptic device

column12: SIMPLE PARTICULATE EMISSIONS MEASURING INSTRUMENT, SYSTEM AND METHOD
column13: A real-time, integrated instrument, method and system based on Radio-frequency (RF) technology to measure over time the carbon core particulates and volatiles in an exhaust gas from a diesel engine's exhaust. The measurement method involves the two stages of (1) Carbon Particulate (CP) concentration by hot filtration and (2) RF-based measurement of accumulated CP which detects changes in the complex permitivity of a gaseous material with CP mixed therein via measuring the amount of attenuation for an RF signal passing through a low loss factor ceramic membrane-coated filter (Ceramem filter) between two antennaes. The system is capable of monitoring solid particles and liquid droplets that condense from exhaust emissions during cool air dilution, including soluble organic fraction (SOF), elemental carbon and sulfate particulates (SO4) or hydrated sulfuric acid, by using this diesel particulate filter (DPM) made with cordierite wall-flow monolith having square passageways lined with ceramic particulate layers functioning as a surface filter.

column12: Coating solutions of trivalent chromium for coating zinc surfaces
column13: Aqueous acidic coating solutions are described for treating zinc or zinc alloy surfaces comprising trivalent chromium as substantially the only chromium ion present, fluoride ion, an acid other than nitric acid, and an oxidizing agent. The coating solutions containing trivalent chromium as substantially the only chromium ion present preferably are prepared by reducing an aqueous solution of hexavalent chromium with sufficient reducing agent to reduce all of the hexavalent chromium to trivalent chromium. Chromate coatings on zinc and zinc alloy surfaces are produced by contacting said surfaces with an aqueous acidic solution of the invention.

column12: Signal monitoring system
column13: A system is provided for monitoring a composite signal at the brushes of a generator. The composite signal includes an information signal representative of brush arcing and a recurring noise signal. The system includes a gating network which eliminates the noise signal and passes the information signal therethrough. Timing of the gating network is controlled by a pulse forming network. On the occurrence of a noise signal the pulse forming network produces a disabling signal of predetermined time period exceeding the duration of the noise signal. The gating network blocks all signal passage therethrough for the duration of the disabling signal and thereafter passes signals until the occurrence of the next noise signal. Means is also provided for indicating when the information signal exceeds a predetermined magnitude.

column12: PHOTO-REALISTIC SHALLOW DEPTH-OF-FIELD RENDERING FROM FOCAL STACKS
column13: The invention relates to photo-realistic shallow depth-of-field rendering from focal stacks. column12: MSE variable step adaptive filter
column13: A very rapidly converging adaptive filter which uses a variable scale factor for each weight of the filter. The value of the variable scale factor is chosen for each iteration and is based upon the sign changes of the incremental weight change. The variable scale factor exhibits large values when no sign changes occur and smaller values when sign changes occur. The new filter provides considerable improvement in increase of convergence rate and decrease in residual errors even in the presence of heavy noise while requiring only a modest increase in hardware.

column12: Apparatus for monitoring arcing of brushes in a dynamoelectric machine
column13: Apparatus is described for monitoring arcing of brushes used in the transfer of current signals to and from the field of a generator. Electrical signals from the brushes, which are applied to the disclosed monitor for analysis, may include brush arcing signals to be monitored and in addition high-amplitude noise spikes in the same frequency band as the brush arcing signals, the noise spikes thus masking accurate detection of low level brush arcing by conventional devices. A two-stage clipping network is provided in the monitor to raise the brush arcing/noise ratio and thus mitigate the masking effect of the noise spikes without loss of a portion of sampling interval during which arcing may occur. Other features described as part of the brush monitor are discriminator diodes biased for constant threshold sensitivity to maintain arc detection accuracy over a wide range of ambient temperatures; an alarm system which functions to indicate and record the occurrence of brush arcing so that corrective action may be initiated to prevent serious damage to rotor slip rings and brush components; and a reference signal generator which automatically adjusts the level of reference signal used in the alarm system for changes in generator noise level.
column15: BISHOP JAMES S;;KLEMENTOWSKI FRANK M;;SAWADA FRED H

column12: Key cover
column13: This relates to a key cover for covering the head of a key. In one embodiment, the key cover is formed in two pieces, a cover member and a plug. In a second embodiment, the cover member and plug are pivotally connected. The cover member is provided with a cavity for receiving the key head with the blade of the key passing through a slot in the underside of the cover member. A plug is then readily insertable into the top of a cavity in overlying relation to the key head disposed within the cavity of the cover member and locked in place with the cover member. The interlock between the plug and the cover member is one wherein the plug cannot be readily removed unless the cover, for all practical purposes, is locked in place on the key. This permits the key cover to be individually applied to a key without materially disassociating the key from its respective lock.

column12: MSE VARIABLE STEP ADAPTIVE FILTER
column13: A very rapidly converging adaptive filter which uses a variable scale factor for each weight of the filter. The size of the variable scale factor is chosen for each iteration and is based upon the sign changes of the incremental weight change. The variable scale factor permits large step sizes when no sign changes occur and smaller step sizes when sign changes occur. The new filter provides considerable improvement in convergence rate and residual errors even in the presence of heavy noise while requiring only a modest increase in hardware.

column12: Magnesium ion based synaptic device
column13: A method of fabricating a synaptic device is provided. The method includes forming a channel layer between a first terminal and a second terminal. The channel layer varies in resistance based on a magnesium concentration in the channel layer. The method further includes forming an electrolyte layer. The electrolyte layer includes a magnesium ion conductive material. A third terminal is formed over the electrolyte layer and applies a signal to the electrolyte layer and the channel layer.

column12: Pass gate decoder for a multiport memory dEvice that uses a single ported memory cell array structure
column13: Described is a last stage decoder that generates a local word line signal within a bank of a single-ported memory cell array structure. The decoder inputs predecoded global row address signals, as well as predecoded local row address signals. In order to generate the local word line signal, and thus access a memory cell within a given bank, both one predecoded global row address signal, as well as one predecoded local row address signal must be present. The predecoded local row address signal turns on a pass gate transistor, and allows the predecoded global row address signal to pass through the pass gate transistor and create the local word line signal.

column12: ADAPTIVE FILTERS
column13: An adaptive filter has the filter weights adjusted by progressively smaller steps as the final condition is approached, thereby combining rapid convergence with low residual error. The signal may be analog, and converted to digital form. A reference signal is obtained by delaying the input signal, and this si filtered in filter (700), subtracted from the undelayed signal in a subtractor (703), and the error signal, representing the difference, is used for computing the changes in filter weights. When the filter is initialised a set of scaling factors µℓis set and the increments OWein the weights are computed in known manner. When these increments repeatedly change sign, an updating circuit (708-L) reduces the scaling factors so that the increments are reduced in magnitude as the filter approaches its final setting. If the increments are successively of the same sign, the scaling factor is increased. An error threshold detector circuit (709) may be provided which detects a condition in which the error signal e(k) suddenly increases, and this may be used to reset the scaling factors µ to their initial values.

column12: Correcting circuits for colour television signals
column13: 1,043,457. Colour television. BRITISH BROADCASTING CORPORATION. July 2, 1965 [Aug. 10, 1964], No. 32529/64. Heading H4F. The invention relates to correcting circuits for colour television signals and particularly to such signals derived from colour film. As shown, Fig. 6, colour separation signals derived by scanning a colour film, are applied to input terminals 10, 11 and 12 respectively which are connected by separate channels to output terminals 13, 14 and 15 respectively, blanking pulses synchronized with the blanking intervals being applied at an input 16. The " colour gain " section which is used to vary the gain of the three channels to compensate for colour casts visible primarily in the low density parts of the film, i.e. the picture highlights, comprises two controls. Considering the red channel, one of the controls is a twelve-position switch RSW1, ganged to corresponding switches in the other channels, which selects a colour channel, or a suitable combination of two colour channels, and hence an effective colour axis along which increased gain may be applied, the other control being a separate gain control RR1, ganged to corresponding controls in the other channels, which determines the amount of correction, i.e. the magnitude of the gain change. The twelve positions of switch RSW1 represent vectors 30 degrees apart on the colour triangle, red, green and blue being 120 degrees apart, and Fig. 4 illustrates the colour axis associated with each switch position and the coefficients determining the contributions of the primaries to each of the twelve colours. The variations of. gain in the colour-separation signal channels according to the coefficients shown in Fig. 4 are determined by resistors RR3, RR4, RR5 (in the red channel) associated with the twelveposition switch RSW1 and the magnitude of the correction is controlled by the three-gang potentiometer RR1. When the slider of RR1 is connected to the input signal terminal 10, maximum correction is applied, RB being an amplifier having a low input impedance so that a variation in the effective value of RR2 causes a change in the signal current that flows into amplifier RB when correction is applied. Resistors RR3, RR4 and RR5 have values such that the necessary gain changes in the red channel are effected at each switch position according to the coefficients in Fig. 4. When the slider of RR1 is connected to earth, no connection is applied and there is no overall gain change since the input impedance of the amplifier RB is low compared with RR5. Thus the twelve-position, three-gang switch RSW1 &c. and-the three-gang potentiometer RR1 &c. allow the white of the film to be corrected, i.e. compensate for " white crushing." To compensate for "black-stretch" or "black-crush" " the signals derived from the film are passed to variable gain devices which operate non-linearly, referred to as " colour gamma " in Fig. 6. The amplifier RB feeds two non-linear circuits 18 and 19, having black-crush and black-stretch characteristics respectively, Fig. 5 (not shown). The two non-linear signals are available at either end of a potentiometer RR6 and movement of the slider of this potentiometer permits a smooth transition from maximum black-stretch to maximum black-crush through a central position where the effective transfer characteristic of the complete circuit is approximately linear. As for the colour gain control, the twelveposition three-gang switch RSW2 and resistors RR7, RR8 and RR9 select the colour axis along which non-linear compensation is applied. Defects caused by excessive or inadequate general density of the film are compensated for by adjustment of a master lift control 17 and a master gain control RA, GA, BA. The blanking pulses, shown as negative going, are applied from 16 through a circuit D which provides positive and negative going pulses at its two outputs and these pulses are applied to the ends of a potentiometer 17. Circuits D and 17 constitute the master lift control by means of which the D.C. component of all colour separation signals may be varied equally. The slider of 17 adjusting the magnitude and sense of the pulses which are combined with the signals during the blanking intervals in combining circuits RC, GC and BC. The master gain control RA, GA, BA comprises three controls ganged together each comprising a variable attenuator followed by an amplifier of fixed gain.

column12: System and method for developing and implementing intellectual property marketing
column13: The present invention relates to methods for the development and implementation of intellectual property marketing. A targeted innovation to fulfill an internal need is developed. Actions are taken to legally protect the targeted innovation as an intellectual property asset. The intellectual property asset is analyzed to determine a marketing assessment. A decision is made whether to market the intellectual property asset based at least in part on the marketing assessment. If the marketing assessment meets a predetermined threshold, the intellectual property asset is marketed.

column12: ANIMAL LITTER, PROCESS FOR PREPARING ANIMAL LITTER, AND METHOD FOR REMOVAL OF ANIMAL WASTE
column13: A grain-based animal litter is disclosed. In accordance with the invention, the animal litter comprises discrete plural particles of a grain-based substrate, which particles tend to agglomerate into clumps when wetted. The litter of the invention absorbs liquids such as animal excretions, and substantially reduces the odor thereof. Preferably, the substrate is a grain germ; more preferably, the substrate is a corn germ; most preferably, the substrate is washed, spent grain germ. In accordance with a preferred embodiment of the invention, the grain germ is provided in the form of discrete plural granules, each of which granules includes a cohesiveness agent in an amount sufficient to enhance the cohesiveness of the granule.
column15: KENT GAGE A;;MCPHERSON ROGER E;;RAMSDEN STEVEN L;;BISHOP LEONA E;;GUTE FRANK J

column12: Novel methods for cleaning ion implanter components
column13: A method and apparatus for cleaning residue from components of an ion source region of an ion implanter used in the fabrication of microelectronic devices. To effectively remove residue, the components are contacted with a gas-phase reactive halide composition for sufficient time and under sufficient conditions to at least partially remove the residue. The gas-phase reactive halide composition is chosen to react selectively with the residue, while not reacting with the components of the ion source region or the vacuum chamber.

column12: Animal litter, process for preparing animal litter, and method for removal of animal waste
column13: A grain-based animal litter comprising discrete plural particles of a grain-based substrate, which particles tend to agglomerate into clumps when wetted. The litter of the invention absorbs liquids such as animal excretions, and substantially reduces the odor thereof. Preferably, the-substrate is a grain germ; more preferably, the substrate is a corn germ; most preferably, the substrate is washed, spent grain germ. In accordance with a preferred embodiment of the invention, the grain germ is provided in the form of discrete plural granules, each of which granules includes a cohesiveness agent in an amount sufficient to enhance the cohesiveness of the granule.

column12: Pyrimidine Derivatives and Compositions Containing them
column13: 1,181,657. Biologically active compositions containing pyrimidinyl-carbamates. IMPERIAL CHEMICAL INDUSTRIES Ltd. 3 March, 1967 [31 March, 1966], No. 14272/66. Headings A5B and A5E. [Also in Division C2] A biologically active composition comprises a diluent and a 2-amino pyrimidinyl-6-caribamate or a salt thereof, suitably of the formula: wherein X and Y are oxygen or sulphur, R 1 and R 2 , and additionally, R 5 and R 6 , represent hydrogen or substituted or unsubstituted hydrocarbon groups, or together with the adjacent N-atom, a substituted or unsubstituted heterocyclic ring and R 3 and R 4 represent hydrogen or halogen atoms, substituted or unsubstituted hydrocarbon groups joined directly or through an O-, S- or N- atom to the pyrimidine ring, or together represent an alkylene bridging group. The active compounds or compositions containing them may be applied to animals (A) externally in the form of dips, sprays, dusting powders or ointments, (B) orally in the form of tablets, capsules, boluses, suspensions, emulsions or solutions when the compositions may contain inert carriers, lubricating agents, and granulating and disintegrating agents, or (C) parenterally in the form of sterile solutions, suspensions or emulsions which may also contain conventional excipients such as solvents or vegetable oils. The veterinary compositions may also contain other substances of known veterinary utility such as anthelmintics and/or bactericides. The active compounds or compositions containing them may also be applied to plants, to seeds or to soil, or to surfaces to exhibit a fumigant effect. As described above, the other additives which may be added to the active composition depend on whether the composition is to be used for agricultural, horticultural or veterinary purposes. The diluent may be a solid (e.g. a granular or fertilizer material) or a liquid (e.g. water or an organic solvent and other additives e.g. adhesives, wetting agents, fillers, suspending agents, dispersing agents, emulsifying agents, fertilizers and other biologically active compounds, may be present. The active composition suitably contains from 0.001 to 85% by weight of the active compound and it may be stabilized by the addition of a stabilizing agent such an epoxide, e.g. epichlorohydrin.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR DETERMINING THE MARKETABILITY OF INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY ASSETS
column13: The present invention relates to methods and systems for determining whether to market an intellectual property asset, where the intellectual property asset is based at least in part on an innovation developed for an internal need. In an embodiment, a description of an intellectual property asset is received, and an assessment of the marketability of the intellectual property asset is generated based at least in part on the description of an intellectual property asset and a marketing criterion.

column12: Gas turbine component with reduced cooling air requirement
column13: Introducing a plurality of geometrically shaped members ( 27 ) into a cooling passage ( 16 ) of a gas turbine airfoil ( 10 ) will effectively reduce the cross-sectional flow area while simultaneously retaining a sufficiently thick external contour desired for proper gas path aerodynamic behavior. Small cooling sub-passages ( 18 a , 18 b ) formed around the geometric members will create a preferentially higher coolant flow rate and heat transfer coefficient at the cooled surface ( 14 ) when compared to the interior of the cavity. The geometric shapes may be metal or ceramic spheres retained in the cooling cavity by a retaining structure such as a screen grid ( 30 ) or perforated plate ( 32 ). The openings ( 34 ) in the retaining structure may be unevenly distributed to preferentially allow more coolant to enter the cavity proximate the cooled walls. The size/shape of the geometrically shaped members may be varied to achieve a desired heat transfer coefficient along the cooled wall surface ( 17 ).
column15: DALTON JOHN P;;AUF DEM KAMPE TILMANN;;MAICHLE FRANK A;;SMITH REX A;;BISHOP STUART P;;IRMISCH STEFAN

column12: NOVEL METHODS FOR CLEANING ION IMPLANTER COMPONENTS
column13: A method and apparatus for cleaning residue from components of the vacuum chamber and beamline of an ion implanter used in the fabrication of microelectronic devices. To effectively remove residue, the components are contacted with a gas-phase reactive halide composition for sufficient time and under sufficient conditions to at least partially remove the residue. The gas-phase reactive halide composition is chosen to react selectively with the residue, while not reacting with the components of the ion source region of the vacuum chamber.
column15: DIMEO FRANK JR;;DIETZ JAMES;;OLANDER W KARL;;KAIM ROBERT;;BISHOP STEVEN E;;NEUNER JEFFREY W;;ARNO JOSE I

column12: FLUID STORAGE AND DISPENSING SYSTEM INCLUDING DYNAMIC FLUID MONITORING OF FLUID STORAGE AND DISPENSING VESSEL
column13: A monitoring system (100) for monitoring fluid in a fluid supply vessel (22, 24, 26, 28, 108) during operation including dispensing of fluid from the fluid supply vessel. The monitoring system includes (i) one or more sensors (114, 126) for monitoring a characteristic of the fluid supply vessel or the fluid dispensed therefrom, (ii) a data acquisition module (40, 132, 146) operatively coupled to the one or more sensors to receive monitoring data therefrom and responsively generate an output correlative to the characteristic monitored by the one or more sensors, and (iii) a processor (50, 150) and display (52, 150) operatively coupled with the data acquisition module and arranged to process the output from the data acquisition module and responsively output a graphical representation of fluid in the fluid supply vessel, billing documents, usage reports, and/or resupply requests.

column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To clean residues from components of a beam line and a vacuum chamber of an ion implanter used in fabrication of microelectronic devices.SOLUTION: To effectively remove the residues, the components are brought into contact with a gas-phase reactive halide composition for sufficient time and under sufficient conditions to at least partially remove the residues. The gas-phase reactive halide composition is chosen to react selectively with the residues while not reacting with the components of the ion source region of the vacuum chamber.

column12: Fluid storage and dispensing system including dynamic fluid monitoring of fluid storage and dispensing vessel
column13: A monitoring system for monitoring fluid in a fluid supply vessel during operation including dispensing of fluid from the fluid supply vessel. The monitoring system includes (i) one or more sensors for monitoring a characteristic of the fluid supply vessel or the fluid dispensed therefrom, (ii) a data acquisition module operatively coupled to the one or more sensors to receive monitoring data therefrom and responsively generate an output correlative to the characteristic monitored by the one or more sensors, and (iii) a processor and display operatively coupled with the data acquisition module and arranged to process the output from the data acquisition module and responsively output a graphical representation of fluid in the fluid supply vessel, billing documents, usage reports, and/or resupply requests.

column12: System and method for selecting and protecting intellectual property assets
column13: The present invention relates to systems and methods for intellectual property asset selection and protection. In an embodiment, an intellectual property selection system receives from an innovator an innovation submission describing an innovation. An intellectual property protection system receives at least a portion of the innovation submission and manages obtaining an intellectual property legal right related to the innovation. An intellectual property asset management system receives and stores at least one of an innovation description is based at least in part on the at least a portion of the innovation submission and the intellectual property legal right description is based at least in part on the intellectual property legal right.

column12: Method and system for processing intelligence information
column13: A method and system for routing intelligence information related to security. The security system provides rules that identify conditions and routing instructions that are to be applied to intelligence information. A security organization may create and modify rules to ensure the appropriate routing of intelligence information in a timely manner. The security system may receive intelligence information from various sources. Regardless of the form or source of intelligence information, the security system analyzes the intelligence information to determine whether any conditions of the rules are satisfied. When a condition of a rule is satisfied, the security system sends a notification of the intelligence information in accordance with the routing instructions for that rule. In this way, intelligence information can be automatically and quickly routed to the appropriate security personnel for further processing.

column12: Cleaning of semiconductor processing systems
column13: A method and apparatus for cleaning residue from components of semiconductor processing systems used in the fabrication of microelectronic devices. To effectively remove residue, the components are contacted with a gas-phase reactive material for sufficient time and under sufficient conditions to at least partially remove the residue. When the residue and the material from which the components are constructed are different, the gas-phase reactive material is selectively reactive with the residue and minimally reactive with the materials from which the components of the ion implanter are constructed. When the residue and the material from which the components are constructed is the same, then the gas-phase reactive material may be reactive with both the residue and the component part. Particularly preferred gas-phase reactive materials utilized comprise gaseous compounds such as XeF 2 , XeF 4 , XeF 6 , NF 3 , IF 5 , IF 7 , SF 6 , C 2 F 6 , F 2 , CF 4 , KrF 2 , Cl 2 , HCl, ClF 3 , ClO 2 , N 2 F 4 , N 2 F 2 , N 3 F, NFH 2 , NH 2 F, HOBr, Br 2 , C 3 F 8 , C 4 F 8 , C 5 F 8 , CHF 3 , CH 2 F 2 , CH 3 F, COF 2 , HF, C 2 HF 5 , C 2 H 2 F 4 , C 2 H 3 F 3 , C 2 H 4 F 2 , C 2 H 5 F, C 3 F 6 , and organochlorides such as COCl 2 , CCl 4 , CHCl 3 , CH 2 Cl 2 and CH 3 Cl.

column12: Cleaning method and apparatus of semiconductor processing systems
column13: The invention relates to a cleaning method and apparatus of semiconductor processing systems, and particularly relates to a method for cleaning one or more componets of an ion implanting system to at least partially remove the ionizing related residue, including that the one or more components are contacted with a gas-phase reactive material to at least partially remove the residue under the condition that the gas-phase reactive material can take a reaction with the residue. The method and apparatus provided can minimize the danger exposed in an interhalogen compound.
column15: FRANK DIMEO;;JAMES DIETZ;;OLANDER KARL W;;ROBERT KAIM;;STEVEN BISHOP;;NEUNER JEFFREY W;;JOSE ARNO;;MARGANSKI PAUL J;;SWEENEY JOSEPH D;;DAVID ELDRIDGE;;SHARAD YEDAVE;;OLEG BYL;;STAUF GREGORY T

column12: CLEANING OF SEMICONDUCTOR PROCESSING SYSTEMS
column13: A method and apparatus for cleaning residue from components of semiconductor processing systems used in the fabrication of microelectronic devices. To effectively remove residue, the components are contacted with a gas-phase reactive material for sufficient time and under sufficient conditions to at least partially remove the residue. When the residue and the material from which the components are constructed are different, the gas-phase reactive material is selectively reactive with the residue and minimally reactive with the materials from which the components of the ion implanter are constructed. When the residue and the material from which the components are constructed is the same, then the gas-phase reactive material may be reactive with both the residue and the component part. Particularly preferred gas-phase reactive materials utilized comprise gaseous compounds such as XeF 2 , XeF 4 , XeF 6 , NF 3 , IF 5 , IF 7 , SF 6 , C 2 F 6 , F 2 , CF 4 , KrF 2 , Cl 2 , HCl, ClF 3 , ClO 2 , N 2 F 4 , N 2 F 2 , N 3 F, NFH 2 , NH 2 F, HOBr, Br 2 , C 3 F 8 , C 4 F 8 , C 5 F 8 , CHF 3 , CH 2 F 2 , CH 3 F, COF 2 , HF, C 2 HF 5 , C 2 H 2 F 4 , C 2 H 3 F 3 , C 2 H 4 F 2 , C 2 H 5 F, C 3 F 6 , and organochlorides such as COCl 2 , CCl 4 , CHCl 3 , CH 2 Cl 2 and CH 3 Cl.

column12: Cleaning of semiconductor processing systems
column13: A method and apparatus for cleaning residue from components of an ion soirce region of an ion implanter used in the fabrication of microelectronic devices. To effectively remove residue, the components are contacted with a gas-phase reactive halide composition for sufficient time and under sufficient conditions to at least partially remove the residue. When the residue and the material from which the components are construced are different, the halide composition is selectively reactive with the residue and minimally reactive with the materials from which the components of the ion implanter are constructed. When the residue and the material from which the components are constructed is the same, then the halide composition may be reactive with both the residue and the component part. Particularly preferred reactive halide cleaning compositions comprise gaseous halide compounds such as XeF2, XeF4, XeF6, NF3, IF5, IF7, SF6, C2F6, F2, CF4, KrF2, Cl2, HC1, C1F3, CIO2, N2F4, N2F2, N3F, NFH2, NH2F, HOBr, Br2, C3F8, C4F8, C5F8, CHF3, CH2F2, CH3F, COF2, HF, C2HF5, C2H2F4, C2H3H3, C2H4F2, C2H5F, C3F6, and organochlorides such as COCl2, CCl4, CHCl3, CH2Cl2 and CH3Cl.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR TREATING BENIGN PROSTATIC HYPERPLASIA WITH LIGHT-ACTIVATED DRUG THERAPY
column13: A photoreactive agent and a drug therapy device including a support member configured to pass through a urethra having proximal and distal ends and a longitudinal internal lumen. A light generator carried by the support member, potted within the lumen, and positioned within the urethra to deliver light to the prostate. The light generator generates a light band with a peak at a preselected wavelength. A power source external to the support member powers the light generator. The positioning element locates the support member within the urethra. A transparent/translucent, integral window is positioned proximate to the prostate and allows light to pass through. The window extends 360 degrees radially from the support member. The light generator has at least LEDs or LOs having a dimension of approximately 0.3 mm×0.3 mm×0.1 mm (length×width×thickness).

column12: System and method for managing intellectual property
column13: The present invention relates to methods and systems for intellectual property management. In an embodiment, a system includes an intellectual property asset inventory system to manage an inventory of intellectual property assets. A product inventory system manages an inventory of products, where the inventory of products correspond to a plurality of products and one or more of the products of the plurality of products are associated with one or more of the intellectual property assets of the plurality of intellectual property assets. A marketing management system manages a plurality of marketing projects, where one or more of the marketing projects of the plurality of marketing projects are associated with at least one of (i) one or more products of the plurality of products, and (ii) one or more intellectual property assets of the plurality of intellectual property assets.

column12: System and method for managing intellectual property
column13: The present invention relates to methods and systems for intellectual property management. In an embodiment, a system includes an intellectual property asset inventory system to manage an inventory of intellectual property assets. A product inventory system manages an inventory of products, where the inventory of products correspond to a plurality of products and one or more of the products of the plurality of products are associated with one or more of the intellectual property assets of the plurality of intellectual property assets. A marketing management system manages a plurality of marketing projects, where one or more of the marketing projects of the plurality of marketing projects are associated with at least one of (i) one or more products of the plurality of products, and (ii) one or more intellectual property assets of the plurality of intellectual property assets.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR MANAGING INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY
column13: The present invention relates to methods and systems for intellectual property management. In an embodiment, a system includes an intellectual property asset inventory system to manage an inventory of intellectual property assets. A product inventory system manages an inventory of products, where the inventory of products corresponds to a plurality of products and one or more of the products of the plurality of products are associated with one or more of the intellectual property assets of the plurality of intellectual property assets. A marketing management system manages a plurality of marketing projects, where one or more of the marketing projects of the plurality of marketing projects are associated with at least one of (i) one or more products of the plurality of products, and (ii) one or more intellectual property assets of the plurality of intellectual property assets.
